\strike                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     \strike0\fs34\par
# High Priority \f2\endash  \f0\lang1036 Good\f2\lang12  performance impact, generally safe.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\fs24\par
\b\fs28 Primary Video Adapter = Ext Graphics (PEG)\b0\fs22                                                                                                                        #\cf3\b\i\fs24  Select this if you are using a dedicated GPU instead of the integrated graphics.\cf0\fs28       \b0\i0\fs24 Sets the primary video output to the PCIe/PEG graphics card, ensuring the system initializes and uses the external GPU for display and rendering.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Global C-state Control = \cf6 Disabled\cf0\f0\lang1036  \f2\lang12  \b0\i\f0\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\i\f2\fs24\lang12 C-states \i0 are CPU power-saving modes that reduce voltage and frequency when the processor is idle. While useful for energy efficiency, they can introduce small delays when the CPU needs to wake back up to full speed. Disabling Global C-state Control keeps the CPU in a high-performance state at all times, eliminating those transition delays and improving real-time responsiveness.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 DF Cstates = \cf6 Disabled\cf0\f0\lang1036   \b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12  \f0\lang1036   \f2\lang12                       \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Disables \i Data Fabric C-States\i0 , keeping interconnect links between CPU cores, memory controller, and other components active at all times. This reduces latency for memory and cache access but increases idle power consumption. If set to Auto, it synchronizes with the Global C-State setting.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 ECO Mode = \cf6 Disabled\cf0\f0\lang1036   \b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12               \f0\lang1036   \f2\lang12          \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Disables th\f0\lang1036 e\f2\lang12  power-saving profile that can limit CPU or SoC performance to conserve energy. Turning it off allows the system to operate at its maximum performance potential at all times.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 SVM Mode = \cf6 Disabled\cf0\f0\lang1036   \b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Disables AMD Secure Virtual Machine (virtualization) for reduced CPU overhead unless virtualization is required.\f0\lang1036  AMD Secure Virtual Machine (SVM), the hardware virtualization feature that allows running multiple operating systems simultaneously using virtual machines. Disabling SVM reduces CPU overhead and slightly improves single-threaded performance, since the processor no longer needs to manage virtualization extensions. \i Keep it enabled only if you plan to use virtualization software such as VMware, VirtualBox, or Hyper-V.\i0\par
\strike\fs22\lang12                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 SR-IOV Support = \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24 Disables Single Root I/O Virtualization (SR-IOV), a feature that allows a single physical PCIe device (typically network cards) to present multiple virtual functions for use by virtual machines. Disabling SR-IOV reduces unnecessary system overhead and potential latency if you are not running virtualized environments that require this feature. This can slightly improve system efficiency in standard desktop or gaming workloads.\par
\strike\fs22\lang12                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Spread Spectrum / Spread Spectrum Control = \cf6 Disabled\cf0\f0\lang1036   \b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Spread Spectrum is a feature that intentionally introduces tiny fluctuations to the system clock frequency in order to reduce electromagnetic interference (EMI). While this helps with radio interference compliance, it slightly destabilizes the clock signal from a performance standpoint. Disabling Spread Spectrum locks the clock frequency to a more consistent value, improving overclocking stability and reducing timing jitter, which benefits latency-sensitive workloads like competitive gaming and real-time audio processing.\par
\b\fs28 PCIe Spread Spectrum = \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 This setting applies the same principle to the PCI Express bus. When enabled, it introduces minor frequency modulation on the PCIe link to reduce EMI from GPUs, storage devices, and other PCIe hardware. While harmless for stock configurations, it can slightly degrade high-speed stability and increase latency. Disabling it ensures that PCIe clock signals remain steady, which can help stabilize GPUs and NVMe drives under heavy load.\fs22\par
\b\fs28 SB Clock Spread Spectrum - \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Turns off frequency modulation on the SouthBridge clock, ensuring stable and consistent timing for SATA, USB, and other chipset-controlled devices. This helps reduce potential latency fluctuations.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 DRAM Latency Enhance = \cf6 Enabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 This option applies more aggressive DRAM timing profiles internally, reducing the delay between memory requests and responses. Enabling it can lead to lower overall memory latency and slightly higher memory bandwidth, which directly improves frame times and computational performance in memory-intensive workloads.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\lang1036\par
\b\fs28 AMD Cool&Quiet Function = \cf6 Disabled \cf0\b0\fs24 (\cf3\i\fs22 recommended for gaming/low latency\cf0\i0\fs24 )\fs22                 Disables AMD\rquote s Cool&Quiet power-saving feature, which dynamically lowers CPU frequency and voltage during low load. While this reduces power consumption and heat, it can introduce small delays when returning to full performance. Disabling it keeps CPU frequencies stable, improving performance consistency and responsiveness in latency-sensitive workloads such as competitive gaming.\par
\strike\lang12                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Chipset Power Saving Features = \cf6 Disabled \f0\lang1036  \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Disables all chipset-level power savings to maintain full responsiveness.\f0\lang1036  Disables all power-saving mechanisms at the chipset level, including features that dynamically reduce power to PCIe lanes, memory controllers, and other integrated components. By turning these off, the system maintains full responsiveness and consistent performance, particularly under heavy workloads or during gaming, where latency spikes from power state transitions can affect stability and frame times. This ensures the chipset operates at maximum efficiency at all times, at the cost of slightly higher power consumption.\par
\strike\fs22\lang12                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 HPET (High Precision Event Timer) = \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 HPET is a hardware timer designed for high precision. However, modern CPUs have a more efficient timer called the Time Stamp Counter (TSC) that is often faster. Disabling HPET forces the OS to use TSC, which can reduce overhead in certain workloads and improve latency, though results vary depending on the system and application.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 SoC/Uncore OC Mode = \cf6 Enabled\b0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                                       \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 The System-on-Chip (SoC) and \ldblquote Uncore\rdblquote  areas of a CPU handle tasks outside the core compute units, such as memory controllers, cache, and interconnects. Enabling SoC/Uncore overclocking allows these subsystems to operate at higher-than-stock speeds, potentially increasing memory throughput, improving cache latency, and accelerating communication between CPU cores and other components.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 ACPI _CST C1 Declaration = \cf6 Disabled\b0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                                                   \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 This setting modifies the Advanced Configuration and Power Interface (ACPI) behavior to prevent the CPU from entering certain low-power idle states like C1. This reduces power savings but ensures the CPU is always ready to execute instructions with minimal delay, improving wake-up times.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Power Down Enable = \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036   \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 When enabled, this setting allows DRAM to enter deep power-down states to save energy when idle. However, waking the memory back up adds delay. Disabling Power Down keeps the DRAM always ready to respond, boosting stability and responsiveness in high-performance workloads.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 PCIe Clock Gating = \cf6 Disabled \f0\lang1036  \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Keeps PCIe clock signals active at all times, preventing power-saving delays when\f0\lang1036  \f2\lang12 devices resume activity. Reduces latency at the cost of slightly higher power draw.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\fs24\par
\b\fs28 Command Rate = \cf6 1T \f0\lang1036  \cf0\b0\i (\fs22 recommended +, but need test\fs28 )\f2\lang12                 \b\i0                            \f0\lang1036                                                                                                       \cf3\i\fs24 # recommend this to drastically reduce latency and improve performance, but you need stable memory and timings / stable RAM!\cf0\b0\i0  \cf3\b\i May cause RAM crash or instability. \cf0\b0\i0                                                                                                                            \f2\lang12 Forces the DRAM command rate to 1T (1 clock per command) instead of 2T, reducing access latency. This can improve \f0\lang1036 P\f2\lang12 erformance\f0\lang1036  and Latency\f2\lang12  but may reduce stability if the memory overclock is aggressive.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\fs24\par
\b\fs28 Gear Down Mode = \cf6 Disabled \f0\lang1036  \cf0\b0\i (\fs22 recommended +, but need test\fs28 )\f2\lang12          \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                     # S\cf3\b\i\fs24 ame like Command Rate, recommend to drastically reduce latency and improve performance, but you need stable memory and timings!\cf0\f2\lang12  \cf3\f0\lang1036 May cause RAM crash or instability. \cf0\i0                                                                                                                            \i\f2\lang12       \i0                           \fs28\par
\b0\fs24 Gear Down Mode simplifies DRAM command timing by reducing the command clock rate, which improves compatibility but increases latency. Disabling it maintains the full-speed command rate for lower latency, although some weaker memory modules may become unstable.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 LCLK DPM = \cf6 Disabled                                    \b0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                         \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 LCLK Dynamic Power Management adjusts the link clock speed dynamically to save power, but frequency changes can cause latency spikes. Disabling this keeps the link clock frequency stable at all times.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 LCLK DPM Enhanced PCIe Detection = \cf6 Disabled\f0\lang1036  \f2\lang12  \cf0\b0\i\f0\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 This is an additional layer of PCIe link clock management tied to LCLK DPM. Disabling it prevents the system from attempting enhanced PCIe device detection routines that can alter clock speeds, improving consistency.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Fast Short REP MOVSB = \cf6 Enabled \f0\lang1036  \f2\lang12  \cf0\b0\i\f0\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 REP MOVSB is a CPU instruction for moving blocks of data in memory. Enabling the \ldblquote Fast Short\rdblquote  optimization speeds up these transfers for small data blocks, improving CPU throughput in scenarios where rapid short memory copies are common.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Enhanced REP MOVSB/STOSB = \cf6 Enabled  \cf0\b0\i\f0\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0 E\f2\fs24\lang12 xtends the optimization of REP MOVSB and STOSB instructions for both memory copying and storing, improving efficiency for workloads that involve repeated memory operations.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 REP-MOV/STOS Streaming = \cf6 Enabled  \cf0\b0\i\f0\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\f2\fs24\lang12 Allows REP MOVSB and STOSB instructions to operate in a streaming mode, optimizing the data transfer path for high throughput.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
 \b\fs28 BankGroupSwap = \cf6 Disabled \f0\lang1036  \cf0\b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0 Controls how DRAM bank groups are accessed. While enabling it can improve compatibility with some memory modules, it may introduce slight latency. Disabling Bank Group Swapping ensures a more direct access pattern, potentially improving memory performance and reducing delays.\par
\b\f2\fs28\lang12 SB Clock Spread Spectrum Option = \cf6 0.362% \cf0 / (or the lowest value)\f0\lang1036  \b0\i (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0                                                                                         \par
\f2\fs24\lang12 Controls the spread spectrum of the SouthBridge PLL, which affects SATA, USB, and other chipset-controlled devices. Setting it to the lowest value (~0.362%) reduces clock fluctuations, helping to slightly improve system responsiveness and minimize latency in I/O operations.\par
\strike\f0\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\f2\par
\b\fs28 Above 4G Decoding = \cf6 Enabled \cf0 (si GPU r\f0\'e9cent)  \b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 Enables the system to allocate more than 4 GB of address space for PCIe devices. This is essential for modern GPUs, particularly in multi-GPU setups or when using Re-Size BAR, ensuring proper memory mapping and compatibility.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 Re-Size BAR Support = \cf6 Enabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 Allows the CPU to access the GPU\rquote s full VRAM in a single range instead of 256 MB chunks. This can improve performance in certain modern games by reducing overhead and increasing data throughput between CPU and GPU.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 Enable Hibernation = \cf6 0  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                   \cf7\b\i\fs28 # Needs testing: in very rare cases, this may cause system /GPU crashes.\cf0\b0\i0\fs22\lang12     \fs24 Disables operating system-level hibernation, which saves the system state to disk when the computer is put into a low-power state. Turning hibernation off prevents potential issues such as audio dropouts, delayed wake times, or driver initialization delays, providing a faster and more responsive resume experience. This is particularly beneficial for users who require immediate system responsiveness after sleep or shutdown, such as gamers or real-time application users.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 PX Dynamic Mode = \cf6 Disabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 PX Dynamic Mode is a PCI Express feature that dynamically changes the allocation of PCIe lanes to different devices depending on workload demand. While useful for power saving and flexible lane usage, it can introduce switching delays or momentary instability. Disabling this feature locks lane allocation, improving overall PCIe stability and reducing latency spikes, particularly important for GPUs or NVMe drives under consistent heavy load.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 PM L1 SS = \cf6 Disabled                                   \b0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                         \cf0\fs24\lang12 PCI Express L1 Substates (L1 SS) are low-power idle modes for PCIe devices that save power when the link is not actively transferring data. Exiting these states requires additional time, potentially introducing micro-latency spikes. Disabling L1 SS keeps PCIe links active and responsive, improving performance in latency-critical situations.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 Unused GPP Clocks Off = \cf6 Disabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 This setting turns off the clocks to unused General Purpose PCIe Ports (GPP) to save power. However, turning clocks back on when needed adds delay. Disabling this option keeps the clocks running at all times, ensuring immediate availability of the PCIe link.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 Fixed SOC Pstate = \cf6 P0                                 \b0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                         \cf0\fs24\lang12 Forces the SoC to operate at its highest performance P-state (P0), ensuring maximum interconnect and memory controller speed at all times.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 PPC Adjustment = \cf6 PState 0                              \b0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                         \cf0\lang12 F\fs24 orces the CPU to report its highest performance state to the OS, ensuring max performance scheduling.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 ACPI Standby State = \cf6 Suspend Disabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 Prevents the system from entering ACPI standby or suspend states. By avoiding power state transitions, this reduces latency when waking or accessing components, ensuring more consistent performance.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 ASPM Support / ASPM Control for CPU / ASPM Mode Control = \cf6 Disabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\b\fs28\lang12\par
\b0\fs24 Disables Active State Power Management (ASPM) on both CPU and chipset sides for all PCIe devices. This prevents PCIe links from entering low-power states, keeping them fully active at all times. The result is reduced latency when accessing PCIe peripherals and more consistent system performance.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\par
\b\fs28 PCIB Clock Run = \cf6 Disabled  \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 Prevents the PCI bus clock from stopping during idle periods. Keeping the bus continuously active ensures immediate responsiveness and slightly lower latency for PCIe communications.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\fs24\par
\b\fs28 USB Phy Power Down = \cf6 Disabled \cf0\b0\i\lang1036 (\cf3\fs22 recommended\cf0\fs28 )\cf3\f2\lang12                        \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036                                    \i\f2\fs28\lang12         \i0\f0\fs22\lang1036     \cf0\fs24\lang12 Disables the power-down of the USB physical layer (PHY) in S4/S5 states. Keeping the USB PHY powered ensures immediate device detection and eliminates potential delays when waking from sleep or powering on, which is beneficial for maintaining responsiveness with USB peripherals such as keyboards and mice.\par
\strike\fs22                                                                                                                                                                                                   \strike0\fs24\par
\b\fs28 SATA Slumber State Capability = \cf6 Disabled              \b0\fs22\lang1036                                                                                         \cf0\fs24\lang12 Disables SATA slumber states to keep drives responsive at all times.\par
\b\fs28 Aggressive SATA Device Sleep Port 0 = \cf6 Disabled         \b0\fs22\lang1036                                             \cf0\fs24\lang12 Prevents Port 0 SATA device from entering aggressive sleep mode, ensuring immediate readiness.\fs22\par
\b\fs28 Aggressive SATA Device Sleep Port 1 = \cf6 Disabled         \b0\fs22\lang1036                                             \cf0\fs24\lang12 Same as above, but for Port 1.\par
